values.text:
Your advisor is Dr. Reshmi Mitra.
She can be emailed at "rmitra\@semo.edu". 
She can also be contacted at 573-651-2920. 
Note, she may be busy and may take time to reponse to your queries. You should prefer using this assistant for queries and reach out to her if the assistant is not able to satisfy your queries.

CY630--Hardware Security<hr>This course covers hardware physical attacks and security primitives; debugging, applicability techniques of hardware security within ecosystems. Prerequisites: CS 500; CS 503. (3 credit hours).

CS690--Graduate Project<hr>Evaluate and defend selected activities such as projects, papers, etc.,completed during the student’s period of study. Prerequisites: consent of department chairperson or graduate coordinator; enrollment in final semester of degree program. (0 credit hour).

CY520--Information Security in Systems Administration<hr>Information security, security constructs, secure software development, and authorization models. Security administration of networking elements, databases, operating and cloud based systems. Prerequisites: CS 380 and CS 480, or CS 503; with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).
CS698--Thesis Research II<hr>Research leading to thesis as directed by advisor and/or chair of thesis committee. Prerequisites: CS 697. (3 credit hours).

Hello. I will be your graduate assistant today.
I can give you information about Courses, Prerequisites, Graduation, Reduced Course Load and more.
 How may I help you?

Here are your options for waiving prerequisites:
  • Submit a certificate of completion of the pre-req courses, which the student has taken in another regionally accredited university.
  • Show any evidence in form of a letter representing significant experience in programming and introductory Computer Science. This should indicate the date of service and issued on organization standard letterhead.
  • Take the pre-req waiver exam in the Computer Sc department about the programming and computing courses and get a 'B' grade.
Core courses are courses that you must take in order to graduate. The following courses are required for CY majors. More information can be found in your degree works.

CS506--Distributed Cloud Computing<hr>Principles and technologies for distributed cloud computing development. Prerequisites: CS 265 and CS 380 and CS 480; or CS 500 and CS 503; all with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).
CS603--Introduction to Data Analytics<hr>Data collection, analysis and visualization of Big Data. Prerequisites: CS 500; CS 503. (3 credit hours).

CY620--Computer Forensics<hr>Forensic tools for recreating attack scenarios, collecting evidence, analyzing data by observation strategies, debugging, and incidence response. Prerequisites: CS 500; CS 503. (3 credit hours).

CS645--Internet of Things<hr>Covers architectures, protocols, layers, services and applications of a packet network from general Internet to sensor networks. Prerequisites: CS 500; CS 503. (3 credit hours).
CS696--Seminar II<hr>Talks/presentations by invited speakers, faculty and graduate students over major issues and trends in computing. Prerequisites: CS695. (3 credit hours).
CS697--Thesis Research I<hr>Proposal development leading to thesis as directed by advisor and/or chair of thesis committee. Prerequisite: CS 605. (3 credit hours).

values.text:
After you have filled in and sent in your advising form, and your courses have been approved by your advisor, you may register in courses from 9AM to 9PM using the SEMO portal. The last day to add or drop courses is the first friday of classes.
  1. Video guide on how to register for courses

CS585--Formal Systems and Modeling<hr>Course covers nondeterminism, program specification and verification, formal models of computation and languages. Prerequisites: CS 265 or CS 500 with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).

CY655--Research Methods in Cybersecurity<hr>Cybersecurity research methodology in analyzing sources, methods, adversaries, threats, philosophy resulting in completion of a research project. (3 credit hours).
CY670--Secure Operating Environments<hr>Trust frameworks and operation of secure operating environments and secure ecosystems within critical infrastructure. Prerequisites: CY 501. (3 credit hours).

CS632--Emerging and Converging Technologies and Computing<hr>Explores current emerging and converging technologies related in computer applications and their implications. Prerequisites: CS 500; CS 503. (3 credit hours).
CS640--Advanced Database Systems<hr>Covers the major topics on designing, using, and implementing database systems and database applications. (3 credit hours).

CY510--Information Security and Assurance<hr>System security principles, components of system security, information assurance with high assurance software design. Cryptographic principles to design secure systems. Data protection at rest and in motion and evolution of challenges in information security. Prerequisites: CS 265 and CS 380 and CS 480, or CS 500 and CS 503; with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).

CY501--Introduction to Cybersecurity<hr>Advanced overview of the field of Cybersecurity, information assurance terminology, security issues, applied cryptography as well as computer forensics applications and methodology. Pre- or corequisite: CS 265 or CS 500; with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).

dialog_nodes.title: get number of required courses every semester

values.text:
As an international student on a student visa, you must enroll in minimum (9 credits) and maximum(9 credits) every semester to maintain your immigration status. Out of these courses, 2 must be face-to-face course.
However, during COVID, these course can all be online and you will still be able to maintain status. 
Furthermore, if it is your last semester, you may apply for a reduced course load, which will allow you to take less than 9 credit hours. You may also take more than 9 credit hours in your last semester if approved by your advisor and the department chair.
CS575--Advanced Web Development<hr>Latest technologies for the front-end and back-end web development. Prerequisites: CS 265 or CS 500 with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).

CY640--Security of Critical Infrastructure<hr>Vulnerability assessment, asset identification, governance, monitoring, access control, risk, compliance, and defense techniques of critical infrastructure. (3 credit hours).

CS695--Seminar I<hr>Impact of of computing on society; social, professional, ethical, legal and security and privacy issues and responsibilities. Prerequisites: CS300 and CS380 and CS480 or CS500 and CS503; or consent of Department Chairperson. (1 credit hour).

dialog_nodes.title: Get minimum required courses US Citizen

values.text:
As a US citizen, In order to be a full-time student, you need to be enrolled in atleast 9 credits every semester. These can be online or face-to-face.
If you are enrolled in less than 9, you are considered a part-time student.

CS503--Fundamentals of Computing<hr>Covers basic understanding of fundamental concepts in computer organizations, networks, algorithms and operating systems. Prerequisite: consent of department chairperson.  (CS503 does not count towards your degree. However you are required to clear them before you are allowed any regular core or optional course in the subsequent semesters).

CS560--Computer Architecture<hr>Major architectures in modern computer systems, including the evolution of computer architectures. Prerequisites: CS 300 and CS 380 and CS 480; or CS 500 and CS 503; all with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).
CS580--Advanced Robotics<hr>Modern topics in Artificial Intelligence robotics. Prerequisites: CS 300 and CS 380 and CS 480; or CS 500 and CS 503; all with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).

CS609--Advanced Programming Languages<hr>Covers objects, testing, deployment, maintenance of a component base solution and design patterns using object oriented concepts. Prerequisite: CS 500. (3 credit hours).
CS653--Special Topics<hr>Contemporary topics in an area of computer science. Prerequisites: CS 500; CS503. (3 credit hours).

As an international student, if it is your last semester, you may enroll in less than 9 credit hours if approved by your advisor and the department chair. This is called reduced course load. You may apply for reduced course load using the portal (portal.semo.edu)
The elective courses for your degree are constantly changing.
In order to see a list of classes offered in a desired semester, please visit the portal (portal.semo.edu) and go to the student ss tab and click on "Look up Classes".

You can drop courses from the SEMO portal

MA664--Mathematical Cyrptography<hr>Basic concepts of secure communication, classical cryptography and cryptoanalysis, monoalphabetic and polyalphabetic ciphers. Shannon’s theory of secrecy. Modern private-key cryptosystems such as DES, and public-key cryptosystems such as RSA.
Prerequisite: MA223 or MA250 or MA338 or MA245 or MA443 with a grade of ‘C’ or higher. (3 credit hours)

GR698<hr>Written comprehensive examination over the degree program. Students must enroll in GR698 during the final semester, except by permission of the graduate program coordinator. Examination fee applied.

CS500--Fundamentals of Programming<hr>Data structures, algorithms, object orientation and standard libraries with emphasis on practical programming. Prerequisite: consent of department chairperson. (CS500 does not count towards your degree. However you are required to clear them before you are allowed any regular core or optional course in the subsequent semesters).

CS581--Advanced Network Programming<hr>Client-server communication, inter-process communication, and secure networking programming. Prerequisites: CS300 and CS380 and CS480, or CS500 and CS503; with minimum grades of C. (3 credit hours).
CY643--Independent Study<hr>Learn to apply knowledge and skills within a topic in cybersecurity independently under supervision from advisors. (3 credit hours).
CS650--Theory of Computation<hr>Models of computation and theory of programming languages. Prerequisites: CS500; CS503. (3 credit hours).
CS691--Independent Study<hr>Independent study in Computer Science. (1 credit hour).
CS693--Independent Study<hr>Covers topics in computer science independently under the supervision of advisors. (3 credit hours).
